_PRINTF(3)                   Custom C Library                   _PRINTF(3)

NAME
       _printf - custom formatted output function

SYNOPSIS
       #include "main.h"

       int _printf(const char *format, ...);

DESCRIPTION
       The _printf function writes formatted output to the standard
       output stream (stdout). It is a simplified version of printf(3).

       The format string contains ordinary characters, which are written
       unchanged, and format directives introduced by '%'. Each directive
       is replaced by the corresponding argument.

       This implementation does not handle:
       - flag characters
       - field width
       - precision
       - length modifiers

SUPPORTED CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
       %c     Prints a single character.

       %s     Prints a null-terminated string.

       %d     Prints a signed decimal integer.

       %i     Same as %d.

       %%     Prints a literal '%' character.

RETURN VALUE
       On success, returns the number of characters printed (excluding
       the terminating null byte).

       On error, returns -1.

EXAMPLE
       #include "main.h"

       int main(void)
       {
           _printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');
           _printf("String: %s\n", "Hello");
           _printf("Numbers: %d and %i\n", 42, -9);
           _printf("Percent: %%\n");
           return (0);
       }

SEE ALSO
       printf(3)

DATE
       November 27, 2025

